        <section ids="taking-feature-tags-into-account-when-reading-project-settings" names="taking\ feature\ tags\ into\ account\ when\ reading\ project\ settings">
            <title>Taking feature tags into account when reading project settings</title>
            <paragraph>By default, feature tags are <strong>not</strong> taken into account when reading project settings
                using the typical approaches (<reference internal="True" refuri="../../classes/class_projectsettings#class-projectsettings-method-get-setting"><inline classes="std std-ref">ProjectSettings.get_setting</inline></reference>
                or <reference internal="True" refuri="../../classes/class_object#class-object-private-method-get"><inline classes="std std-ref">ProjectSettings.get</inline></reference>).
                Instead, you must use <reference internal="True" refuri="../../classes/class_projectsettings#class-projectsettings-method-get-setting"><inline classes="std std-ref">ProjectSettings.get_setting_with_override</inline></reference>.</paragraph>
            <paragraph>For example, with the following project settings:</paragraph>
            <literal_block force="False" language="gdscript" linenos="False" xml:space="preserve">[section]

subsection/example = "Release"
subsection/example.debug = "Debug"</literal_block>
            <paragraph>Using <literal>ProjectSettings.get_setting("section/subsection/example")</literal> will return
                <literal>"Release"</literal> regardless of whether a debug build is currently running. On the
                other hand, <literal>ProjectSettings.get_setting_with_override("section/subsection/example")</literal>
                will obey feature tags and will return <literal>"Debug"</literal> if using a debug build.</paragraph>
        </section>
        <section ids="customizing-the-build" names="customizing\ the\ build">
            <title>Customizing the build</title>
            <paragraph>Feature tags can be used to customize a build process too, by writing a custom <strong>ExportPlugin</strong>.
                They are also used to specify which shared library is loaded and exported in <strong>GDExtension</strong>.</paragraph>
